name: AmmoComponent
description: Adds Ammo physics to a Goo entity. Ammo is a powerful physics engine converted from the C language project Bullet. Use Ammo.js if you need to support any 3D shape (trimesh). Also see {@link AmmoSystem}.

params.description: The settings object can contain the following properties:
params.name: settings

params.description: use the model bounds or use the real (must-be-convex) vertices
params.name: settings.useBounds

params.description: use the model world bounds or use the real (must-be-convex) vertices (this setting is experimental)
params.name: settings.useWorldBounds

params.description: use the model world transform instead of local (this setting is experimental)
params.name: settings.useWorldTransform

params.description: show the model world bounding box (this setting is experimental)
params.name: settings.showBounds

examples:
var entity = world.createEntity(new Box(20, 10, 1));
entity.setComponent(new AmmoComponent({ mass: 5 }));

name: dxtToRgb565
description:
Transcodes DXT into RGB565.
Optimizations:
1. Use integer math to compute c2 and c3 instead of floating point
   math.  Specifically:
     c2 = 5/8 * c0 + 3/8 * c1
     c3 = 3/8 * c0 + 5/8 * c1
   This is about a 40% performance improvement.  It also appears to
   match what hardware DXT decoders do, as the colors produced
   by this integer math match what hardware produces, while the
   floating point in dxtToRgb565Unoptimized() produce slightly
   different colors (for one GPU this was tested on).
2. Unroll the inner loop.  Another ~10% improvement.
3. Compute r0, g0, b0, r1, g1, b1 only once instead of twice.
   Another 10% improvement.
4. Use a Uint16Array instead of a Uint8Array.  Another 10% improvement.

params.description: The src DXT bits as a Uint16Array.
params.name: src

ParticleComponents may have one or more emitters. Each emitter spawns particles, controlling spawn rate, lifetime, initial velocity vector and position of each particle. Each Particle System also contains a timeline describing changes each particle should perform over its lifetime, including:
